    "text": {
      "text": "Example, Inc. is in discussions with a buyer to be acquired. The buyer is offering $100M and the projected exit date is April 22, 2021. In addition to the convertible notes, Example, Inc. also has a small loan of $200,000 from The Best Bank. To understand what each of their shareholder’s payouts will be, they run a waterfall exit model on Carta. carta/public/11/images/4836127397698402508_ZVHS7unV0xGI7S_nhxjSDSwSjyAZMu2mTj7R9cqCgT9z3YN45ioiGcc2G9XNZlqirpIcOnELn5vk4gV4AJaA9dMHONUmS1FtpJosB4kNQ5dWbDOFO2TeVXFbnAc1muckqF6K5xy0",
      "originalText": "Example, Inc. is in discussions with a buyer to be acquired. The buyer is offering $100M and the projected exit date is April 22, 2021. In addition to the convertible notes, Example, Inc. also has a small loan of $200,000 from The Best Bank. To understand what each of their shareholder’s payouts will be, they run a waterfall exit model on Carta.<br><img height=\"243\" src=\"carta/public/11/images/4836127397698402508_ZVHS7unV0xGI7S_nhxjSDSwSjyAZMu2mTj7R9cqCgT9z3YN45ioiGcc2G9XNZlqirpIcOnELn5vk4gV4AJaA9dMHONUmS1FtpJosB4kNQ5dWbDOFO2TeVXFbnAc1muckqF6K5xy0\" width=\"624\"><br>&nbsp;",
      "associatedImage": {
        "url": "carta/public/11/images/4836127397698402508_ZVHS7unV0xGI7S_nhxjSDSwSjyAZMu2mTj7R9cqCgT9z3YN45ioiGcc2G9XNZlqirpIcOnELn5vk4gV4AJaA9dMHONUmS1FtpJosB4kNQ5dWbDOFO2TeVXFbnAc1muckqF6K5xy0"
      }
    }
  }, {
    "id": "7209570471805013992",
    "text": {
      "text": "From the breakpoints above, you can see that the non-convertible debt balance of $200,000 and the convertible debt balance of $1M in principal and $35,178 in interest is being paid out first as debt holders typically have the first lien on any payments. In the next breakpoint, the Series Seed preferred holders have a right to receive the next tier in value and at this tier, they will receive their invested amount back. This is often referred to as their liquidation preference. In the next breakpoint, Common stock will start to receive value on their own until the Series Seed preferred shares convert into common. In this example, common will receive value until the common stock is worth $1 (the Series Seed OIP value) at which point the Series Seed preferred shares come in the money and “convert” into common. In the last breakpoint, the convertible notes convert into common and all share classes receive the remaining value together.  In the first 3 breakpoints, the participating share classes are participating alone. For example, Series Seed in the 2nd breakpoint is the only share class participating. This means that the value in tier is entirely distributed to those share class holders. However, once we reach the 4th breakpoint, Series Seed and Common Stock are participating together so the value in tier is divided up by the pro-rata amount participating in each share class.  Once we know each breakpoints value in tier, we can start assigning that value to the participating share classes. To do this, we figure out what percentage of each breakpoint is attributed to each share class. This is roughly what that calculation looks like: carta/public/11/images/1854520535382502332_ihxRhb3e56-vJlK0zx4pDjLfTRDZ9vAHYNLb9N1Bu_4f_0Qf5QKwi7lSzpsYcRH8Owf5nKsQT29b5iYBuMeMFibDK8zIjwSfuw8qmWmVfzmXaBpbPitmOC3G6qBoLM7GDHjzf_Qo  Once we know what percentage of each share class is participating at each breakpoint, then we can figure out what dollar value is attributed to each share class. We do this by taking the value in tier for the breakpoint in question and multiplying that by the % participating. For example, in breakpoint 5 our value in tier is $70,988,997 and 20.10% of that breakpoint is being distributed to the Series Seed stock which means in breakpoint 5, Series Seed is receiving $14,267,833 in value. carta/public/11/images/7658510840913429000_HRC7Tvp5AWG4rn37NQkps3KNEevycpN264pCm2ZpQ-i3unRDVmw4rbCzAdq51xJFn2QLH-2TZbIoBJr71yFUkCW8lrW-JdZ6UfR6U_zYkTd-tY8Q8nO57P74zWTE5RgP4-EL1fxR  The third and final step is to take the per share value for each share class and multiply it by the number of shares held by each of the top 30 shareholders.",
      "originalText": "From the breakpoints above, you can see that the non-convertible debt balance of $200,000 and the convertible debt balance of $1M in principal and $35,178 in interest is being paid out first as debt holders typically have the first lien on any payments. In the next breakpoint, the Series Seed preferred holders have a right to receive the next tier in value and at this tier, they will receive their invested amount back. This is often referred to as their liquidation preference. In the next breakpoint, Common stock will start to receive value on their own until the Series Seed preferred shares convert into common. In this example, common will receive value until the common stock is worth $1 (the Series Seed OIP value) at which point the Series Seed preferred shares come in the money and “convert” into common. In the last breakpoint, the convertible notes convert into common and all share classes receive the remaining value together.<br><br>In the first 3 breakpoints, the participating share classes are participating alone. For example, Series Seed in the 2nd breakpoint is the only share class participating. This means that the value in tier is entirely distributed to those share class holders. However, once we reach the 4th breakpoint, Series Seed and Common Stock are participating together so the value in tier is divided up by the pro-rata amount participating in each share class.<br><br>Once we know each breakpoints value in tier, we can start assigning that value to the participating share classes. To do this, we figure out what percentage of each breakpoint is attributed to each share class. This is roughly what that calculation looks like:<br><img height=\"91\" src=\"carta/public/11/images/1854520535382502332_ihxRhb3e56-vJlK0zx4pDjLfTRDZ9vAHYNLb9N1Bu_4f_0Qf5QKwi7lSzpsYcRH8Owf5nKsQT29b5iYBuMeMFibDK8zIjwSfuw8qmWmVfzmXaBpbPitmOC3G6qBoLM7GDHjzf_Qo\" width=\"624\"><br><br>Once we know what percentage of each share class is participating at each breakpoint, then we can figure out what dollar value is attributed to each share class. We do this by taking the value in tier for the breakpoint in question and multiplying that by the % participating. For example, in breakpoint 5 our value in tier is $70,988,997 and 20.10% of that breakpoint is being distributed to the Series Seed stock which means in breakpoint 5, Series Seed is receiving $14,267,833 in value.<br><img height=\"200\" src=\"carta/public/11/images/7658510840913429000_HRC7Tvp5AWG4rn37NQkps3KNEevycpN264pCm2ZpQ-i3unRDVmw4rbCzAdq51xJFn2QLH-2TZbIoBJr71yFUkCW8lrW-JdZ6UfR6U_zYkTd-tY8Q8nO57P74zWTE5RgP4-EL1fxR\" width=\"624\"><br><br>The third and final step is to take the per share value for each share class and multiply it by the number of shares held by each of the top 30 shareholders.",
