    "text": {
      "text": "In-Depth DLOM Explainer"
    }
  },
  "linked": [{
    "id": "1143189386282485693",
    "text": {
      "text": "Recall in the Options Pricing Model overview, we walked through the OPM to compute a per-share value of$3.05on a fully marketable basis. In other words,ifthe company that we were valuing were publicly traded (i.e., fully marketable),then one would expect to pay$3.05per share for every share of common stock in our example company,ABC, Inc.",
      "originalText": "Recall in the <a href=\"https://support.carta.com/s/article/option-pricing-model\" target=\"_blank\"><u>Options Pricing Mode</u>l</a> overview, we walked through the OPM to compute a per-share value of $3.05 on a fully marketable basis. In other words, if the company that we were valuing were publicly traded (i.e., fully marketable), then one would expect to pay $3.05 per share for every share of common stock in our example company, ABC, Inc."
    }
  }, {
    "id": "691428922677252667",
    "text": {
      "text": "When valuing closely-held (private) companies, however, valuators typically apply adiscount for lack of marketability (DLOM) to the share price, to account for the fact that private company shares are not completelyliquid.In other words, one should expect to payless for a closely-held (private) share of stock than that same investor would pay for a publicly-traded, fully liquid security.",
      "originalText": "When valuing closely-held (private) companies, however, valuators typically apply a discount for lack of marketability (DLOM) to the share price, to account for the fact that private company shares are not completely liquid. In other words, one should expect to pay less&nbsp;for a closely-held (private) share of stock than that same investor would pay for a publicly-traded, fully liquid security."
