  "linked": [{
    "id": "-2339721830310427032",
    "text": {
      "text": "Principal: The amount of cash that the stakeholder paid for the note. For example, if the stakeholder invested $10,000, then $10,000 is the principal amount.",
      "originalText": "Principal: The amount of cash that the stakeholder paid for the note. For example, if the stakeholder invested $10,000, then $10,000 is the principal amount."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "-2965239947538068671",
    "text": {
      "text": "Conversion Discount: The discount applied to the price per share when the note holder will purchase shares in the next fundraising round.  For example, imagine an investor who is owed $10,000 for their convertible investment with a 20% conversion discount. The new equity round is set at a $2.00 price per share. The price per share is discounted by 20%., which calculates to $2.00 x (1 - 0.20) = $1.60. The principal amount is converted using the discounted price per share for a total of 6,250 shares ($10,000 / $1.60).",
      "originalText": "Conversion Discount: The discount applied to the price per share when the note holder will purchase shares in the next fundraising round.<br><br>For example, imagine an investor who is owed $10,000 for their convertible investment with a 20% conversion discount. The new equity round is set at a $2.00 price per share. The price per share is discounted by 20%., which calculates to $2.00 x (1 - 0.20) = $1.60. The principal amount is converted using the discounted price per share for a total of 6,250 shares ($10,000 / $1.60)."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "1207572662073875665",
    "text": {
      "text": "Valuation Cap (optional): The valuation cap sets a maximum value at which a convertible security will convert into equity in the financing round. This valuation cap stands regardless of the valuation of the financing round.  For example, imagine a stakeholder invests $10,000 in a company valued at around $1,000,000 (Note the convertible owner does not own equity at this point). The convertible includes a valuation cap of $5,000,000. Two years later, the company raises a round of financing at a $50,000,000 valuation after experiencing rapid growth. The price per share of the round is $2.00, implying 25,000,000 fully diluted shares ($50,000,000 / $2.00). Had there been no valuation cap (and assuming a 0% discount), the investor would receive 5,000 shares ($10,000 / $2.00) and own 0.02% of the company. With the valuation cap, the investor is protected from a rapid increase in the company’s valuation. Rather than converting at $2.00 / share, the convertible will convert at $0.20 ($5,000,000 / $25,000,000) and the shareholder will receive 50,000 shares ($10,000 / $0.20) for 0.20% ownership of the company.",
      "originalText": "Valuation Cap (optional): The valuation cap sets a maximum value at which a convertible security will convert into equity in the financing round. This valuation cap stands regardless of the valuation of the financing round.<br><br>For example, imagine a stakeholder invests $10,000 in a company valued at around $1,000,000 (Note the convertible owner does not own equity at this point). The convertible includes a valuation cap of $5,000,000. Two years later, the company raises a round of financing at a $50,000,000 valuation after experiencing rapid growth. The price per share of the round is $2.00, implying 25,000,000 fully diluted shares ($50,000,000 / $2.00). Had there been no valuation cap (and assuming a 0% discount), the investor would receive 5,000 shares ($10,000 / $2.00) and own 0.02% of the company. With the valuation cap, the investor is protected from a rapid increase in the company’s valuation. Rather than converting at $2.00 / share, the convertible will convert at $0.20 ($5,000,000 / $25,000,000) and the shareholder will receive 50,000 shares ($10,000 / $0.20) for 0.20% ownership of the company."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "2403708490288153328",
    "text": {
      "text": "Valuation Cap Type: There are two types of valuation caps: pre-money and post-money. The primary difference between the two is how the conversion price is calculated. The conversion price is calculated by dividing the valuation cap by the liquidity capitalization. For post-money valuation caps, the liquidity capitalization includes the shares that will be created from the conversion of the post-money instrument. Pre-money instruments do not include the shares that will be created upon conversion in the capitalization figure. Generally, post-money valuation caps will be explicitly labeled as post-money in the note document. When a valuation cap is stated but not specified, the valuation cap is pre-money.",
      "originalText": "Valuation Cap Type: There are two types of valuation caps: pre-money and post-money. The primary difference between the two is how the conversion price is calculated. The conversion price is calculated by dividing the valuation cap by the liquidity capitalization. For post-money valuation caps, the liquidity capitalization includes the shares that will be created from the conversion of the post-money instrument. Pre-money instruments do not include the shares that will be created upon conversion in the capitalization figure. Generally, post-money valuation caps will be explicitly labeled as post-money in the note document. When a valuation cap is stated but not specified, the valuation cap is pre-money."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "-1208517036833325593",
    "text": {
      "text": "Conversion Price Basis: This determines what securities are included in the capitalization definition that is used to calculate conversion price. This is generally referred to as Liquidity Capitalization or Fully Diluted Capitalization.",
      "originalText": "Conversion Price Basis: This determines what securities are included in the capitalization definition that is used to calculate conversion price. This is generally referred to as Liquidity Capitalization or Fully Diluted Capitalization."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "7306377586493842723",
    "list": {
      "item": [{
        "text": "For post-money cap securities, the capitalization is generally defined as all outstanding shares, all outstanding options, all converting securities (including shares converted from post-money SAFE) but excludes the unissued option pool.",
        "originalText": "For post-money cap securities, the capitalization is generally defined as all outstanding shares, all outstanding options, all converting securities (including shares converted from post-money SAFE) but excludes the unissued option pool."
      }, {
        "text": "For pre-money cap securities, the capitalization is generally defined as all outstanding shares, all outstanding options, may or may not include unissued options and always excludes shares from the conversion of notes.",
        "originalText": "For pre-money cap securities, the capitalization is generally defined as all outstanding shares, all outstanding options, may or may not include unissued options and always excludes shares from the conversion of notes."
      }]
    }
  }, {
    "id": "-665857664921229463",
    "text": {
      "text": "Cash Out Multiplier: This is the multiplier on the payout to the investor if there is a liquidity event prior to the termination of the convertible note or SAFE. If no cash-out multiplier is specified then default to 1x.",
      "originalText": "Cash Out Multiplier: This is the multiplier on the payout to the investor if there is a liquidity event prior to the termination of the convertible note or SAFE. If no cash-out multiplier is specified then default to 1x."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "-7470411212440160303",
    "text": {
      "text": "Liquidation Priority: The liquidation priority section specifies what order SAFEs will be paid out if there is a liquidity event. There is a liquidation priority section for post-money SAFEs, which states if, in a liquidity event, the SAFE will be on par with preferred. If there is no such section in agreement highlighting liquidation priority, the default should just be “senior to preferred.",
      "originalText": "Liquidation Priority: The liquidation priority section specifies what order SAFEs will be paid out if there is a liquidity event. There is a liquidation priority section for post-money SAFEs, which states if, in a liquidity event, the SAFE will be on par with preferred. If there is no such section in agreement highlighting liquidation priority, the default should just be “senior to preferred."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "-7560446362693211296",
    "text": {
      "text": "Applies to these Convertible types: Convertible debt",
      "originalText": "Applies to these Convertible types: Convertible debt"
    },
    "signals": [{
      "valueL": "2"
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "2369770306868767992",
    "text": {
      "text": "Conversion Trigger: For convertibles to convert into the next equity round, terms may be included that specify that the round be of a certain size for the convertible to convert. For example, imagine a convertible note has a $5,000,000 conversion trigger. In this case, the equity round must be for at least $5,000,000 for the convertible securities to be able to convert into equity.",
      "originalText": "Conversion Trigger: For convertibles to convert into the next equity round, terms may be included that specify that the round be of a certain size for the convertible to convert. For example, imagine a convertible note has a $5,000,000 conversion trigger. In this case, the equity round must be for at least $5,000,000 for the convertible securities to be able to convert into equity."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "-9150175397870161395",
    "text": {
      "text": "Federal Exemption: Choosing Federal Exemptions",
      "originalText": "Federal Exemption: <a href=\"https://support.carta.com/s/article/choosing-federal-exemptions\" target=\"_blank\">Choosing Federal Exemptions</a>"
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "-3302200183104074887",
    "text": {
      "text": "Interest Rate: The annual interest rate that the note accrues.  For example, a $10,000 with a 5.00% interest rate will accrue $500 in interest ($10,000 x 5.00%) over the course of the year.",
      "originalText": "Interest Rate: The annual interest rate that the note accrues.<br><br>For example, a $10,000 with a 5.00% interest rate will accrue $500 in interest ($10,000 x 5.00%) over the course of the year."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "8670158362016769423",
    "text": {
      "text": "Interest Type: Choose if the interest on the convertible is simple or compounded.",
      "originalText": "Interest Type: Choose if the interest on the convertible is simple or compounded."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "2596213207246020050",
    "text": {
      "text": "Interest Accrual Period: The length of time over which the interest due to the lender is calculated. For the interest to be reflected more often, choose \"Daily\" or \"Weekly\".",
      "originalText": "Interest Accrual Period: The length of time over which the interest due to the lender is calculated. For the interest to be reflected more often, choose \"Daily\" or \"Weekly\"."
    }
  }, {
    "id": "-5235357632499947007",
    "text": {
      "text": "Interest Compounding Period: Simple interest is calculated only on the principal amount of the loan, while compound interest is calculated on the principal amount and also on the accumulated interest of the previous period. Must be one of: Annually, Semi-annually, Quarterly, Monthly, or Daily.",
      "originalText": "Interest Compounding Period: Simple interest is calculated only on the principal amount of the loan, while compound interest is calculated on the principal amount and also on the accumulated interest of the previous period. Must be one of: &nbsp;Annually, Semi-annually, Quarterly, Monthly, or Daily."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "-4773919973928744627",
    "text": {
      "text": "Interest Payout: A deferred interest payout allows interest on the convertible to be in the form of additional shares (rather than cash) upon conversion of the note in the next financing round. Carta supports either “Cash” or “Deferred” payouts if these terms are included for your notes.",
      "originalText": "Interest Payout: A deferred interest payout allows interest on the convertible to be in the form of additional shares (rather than cash) upon conversion of the note in the next financing round. Carta supports either “Cash” or “Deferred” payouts if these terms are included for your notes."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "-1820423702888599131",
    "text": {
      "text": "Maturity Date: The date on which the convertible note matures. For example, if a note was issued on 1/1/2019 and has a 10-year term, the maturity date will be 1/1/2029. At maturity, the note’s principal and interest must be paid back if the note hasn’t converted into equity.",
      "originalText": "Maturity Date: The date on which the convertible note matures. For example, if a note was issued on 1/1/2019 and has a 10-year term, the maturity date will be 1/1/2029. At maturity, the note’s principal and interest must be paid back if the note hasn’t converted into equity."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }, {
    "id": "7711226196598769418",
    "text": {
      "text": "Change of Control Percent (optional): Use this field if there’s any premium or multiplier applied to the principal in the event of a change in control prior to the maturity date.",
      "originalText": "Change of Control Percent (optional): Use this field if there’s any premium or multiplier applied to the principal in the event of a change in control prior to the maturity date."
    },
    "signals": [{
      "key": "FontBolded",
      "valueB": true
    }]
  }]
}

