        "originalText": "There are some report entries needed:  Report names cannot contain special characters and must be under 40 characters. The start date is not an editable field and will always be determined by the base report. All new reports must build off of an existing report, however you can choose to build off of any existing report at any time, or off of the original issuance date. Choosing a report end date will determine the period of the report, as well as the start date of any reports that will eventually build off of the new report.<br> <img height=\"555\" src=\"carta/public/13/images/27705201108280358_nzP7FBIpHPs1JS1wF_MhGRN53prrD0e9yhSbpkE6Y-7-TXdZRFqHLpOT1yQ-7om-9_9W5I2nwYhxdr4L87g745Kc5520HnxaWtJcNDeAI0StduJEtMmcnqg9DYLUjkv0ddHrV_Zv\" width=\"477\"> Something new in V3 is the concept of bitemporal reporting. Bitemporal reporting allows you to report not just on an effective date but also the date on which a transaction was reported into the system or recorded. Custom record date determines the version of the underlying data on Carta that is used for creation of the report.  Selecting No will use the current version of Carta data, i.e. the state of your cap table when you make the report request. Selecting Yes will allow you to select a previous date and previous version of Carta data. This allows you to run reports for the historical state of your cap table.<br> &nbsp;  For example, if you want your expense reports to match another report generated on Carta at a previous date, you can select the record date equivalent to the date the other report was created. By doing so, you will get the same outcome in your disclosures report as other share activity reports. Carta uses these record dates when building future and historical reports to ensure in and out of period classification is accurate and all share activity is captured in your stock based compensation reports. This is important for any late entered adjustments or entries to your cap table 