{
  "id": "7577290385994212494",
  "subject": {
    "id": "7577290385994212494",
    "text": {
      "text": "How do the mechanics of the subject company transaction method using a Hybrid OPM differ from the mechanics of the subject company transaction method using a single OPM?"
    }
  },
  "linked": [{
    "id": "4752504696231802998",
    "text": {
      "text": "As discussed, the subject company transaction method “backsolves” to a value for the company that allows recent investors to receive their investment back, based on the Option Pricing Model (“OPM”).  Using a Hybrid OPM, we assume a value based on invested capital in the Early Exit scenario. Accordingly, we determine a Late Exit value that results in a value for the recent round of preferred financing equal to the amount invested.  An exhibit from the Hybrid OPM is shown below. carta/public/13/images/2164901953037745530_pR5PWFrXQ81QUazx-f_q5iqMzJcsvJAxGJeF6Hbqdfz8NrlmdLpWKOda_0k7vI2qY80ayTZtw-3uO-y2JqpESqXSUWHeB5FgDASGU8dJur9K2IhDlqSfueCwX-R9EajwaEdhVUjm  This example assumes the company’s capitalization table consists of Series Seed Preferred (a recent, arm’s-length, priced equity round of financing), common shares, and options with a strike price of $0.25. The investors’ invested capital in the Series Seed Preferred financing was $5,000,000, and they paid $1.00 per share. Based on 75.00% weighting on the Early Exit, and 25.00% weighting on the Late Exit, $17,850,000 is the value of the company in the Late Exit that is needed for the Hybrid OPM to result in a weighted price of $1.00 per share of Series Seed Preferred.",
      "originalText": "As discussed, the subject company transaction method “backsolves” to a value for the company that allows recent investors to receive their investment back, based on the Option Pricing Model (“OPM”).<br><br>Using a Hybrid OPM, we assume a value based on invested capital in the Early Exit scenario. Accordingly, we determine a Late Exit value that results in a value for the recent round of preferred financing equal to the amount invested.<br><br>An exhibit from the Hybrid OPM is shown below.<br><img height=\"385\" src=\"carta/public/13/images/2164901953037745530_pR5PWFrXQ81QUazx-f_q5iqMzJcsvJAxGJeF6Hbqdfz8NrlmdLpWKOda_0k7vI2qY80ayTZtw-3uO-y2JqpESqXSUWHeB5FgDASGU8dJur9K2IhDlqSfueCwX-R9EajwaEdhVUjm\" style=\"margin-left: 0px;margin-top: 0px;\" width=\"624\"><br><br>This example assumes the company’s capitalization table consists of Series Seed Preferred (a recent, arm’s-length, priced equity round of financing), common shares, and options with a strike price of $0.25. The investors’ invested capital in the Series Seed Preferred financing was $5,000,000, and they paid $1.00 per share. Based on 75.00% weighting on the Early Exit, and 25.00% weighting on the Late Exit, $17,850,000 is the value of the company in the Late Exit that is needed for the Hybrid OPM to result in a weighted price of $1.00 per share of Series Seed Preferred.",
      "associatedImage": {
        "url": "carta/public/13/images/2164901953037745530_pR5PWFrXQ81QUazx-f_q5iqMzJcsvJAxGJeF6Hbqdfz8NrlmdLpWKOda_0k7vI2qY80ayTZtw-3uO-y2JqpESqXSUWHeB5FgDASGU8dJur9K2IhDlqSfueCwX-R9EajwaEdhVUjm"
      }
    }
  }]
