{
  "id": "-140098802671998024",
  "subject": {
    "id": "-140098802671998024",
    "text": {
      "text": "What is the subject company transaction (\"backsolve\") method?"
    }
  },
  "linked": [{
    "id": "210065276668652484",
    "text": {
      "text": "The subject company transaction (\"backsolve\") method is applicable when your company has sold shares in a recent, arm’s length, priced equity round of financing.  The methodology seeks to answer the following question. Based on the Black-Scholes Option Pricing Model (“OPM”), the rights and preferences of all share classes on the capitalization table, and the price per share of the recent financing (for example, Series Seed Preferred), what does the value of the Company need to be for the recent investors (for example, Series Seed Preferred investors) to receive their investment back? Essentially, the methodology “backsolves” to a value for the company based on the recent financing.  An example OPM exhibit from a report utilizing the subject company transaction method is shown below. carta/public/13/images/8696308067068407727_6rywbaOclam6OAfKD4W9CMz598fHa2uJIj0378OMKP5hRUebVtsoNqLAVaZxjfhNubqCMtgUOvynCCk0BLXTbK8q6uAsjUmyPsJnmbul9U5vXHJxcGA93RgcBb3LfxMFThMkv_fN  This example assumes the company’s capitalization table consists of Series Seed Preferred (a recent, arm’s length, priced-equity round of financing), common shares, and options with a strike price of $0.25. The exhibit above shows the payout to each share class based on the company’s exit value. In this example the company’s exit value is $10,000,000, as confirmed by summing the “Share class value” column.  As discussed, the subject company transaction method “backsolves” to a value for the company that allows recent investors to receive their investment back, based on the OPM. In this example, assuming the analysis was conducted using the subject company transaction method, we can assume Series Seed Preferred investors paid $0.84 per share of Series Seed Preferred, and $10,000,000 is the value of the Company that is needed for the OPM to back into a price of $0.84 per share of Series Seed Preferred. Note: the value allocated to the common stock in this example is not a final conclusion and would be adjusted to incorporate applicable discounts.",
      "originalText": "The subject company transaction (\"backsolve\") method is applicable when your company has sold shares in a recent, arm’s length, priced equity round of financing.&nbsp;<br><br>The methodology seeks to answer the following question. Based on the Black-Scholes Option Pricing Model (“OPM”), the rights and preferences of all share classes on the capitalization table, and the price per share of the recent financing (for example, Series Seed Preferred), what does the value of the Company need to be for the recent investors (for example, Series Seed Preferred investors) to receive their investment back? Essentially, the methodology “backsolves” to a value for the company based on the recent financing.<br><br>An example OPM exhibit from a report utilizing the subject company transaction method is shown below.<br><img height=\"100\" src=\"carta/public/13/images/8696308067068407727_6rywbaOclam6OAfKD4W9CMz598fHa2uJIj0378OMKP5hRUebVtsoNqLAVaZxjfhNubqCMtgUOvynCCk0BLXTbK8q6uAsjUmyPsJnmbul9U5vXHJxcGA93RgcBb3LfxMFThMkv_fN\" style=\"margin-left: 0px;margin-top: 0px;\" width=\"624\"><br><br>This example assumes the company’s capitalization table consists of Series Seed Preferred (a recent, arm’s length, priced-equity round of financing), common shares, and options with a strike price of $0.25. The exhibit above shows the payout to each share class based on the company’s exit value. In this example the company’s exit value is $10,000,000, as confirmed by summing the “Share class value” column.<br><br>As discussed, the subject company transaction method “backsolves” to a value for the company that allows recent investors to receive their investment back, based on the OPM. In this example, assuming the analysis was conducted using the subject company transaction method, we can assume Series Seed Preferred investors paid $0.84 per share of Series Seed Preferred, and $10,000,000 is the value of the Company that is needed for the OPM to back into a price of $0.84 per share of Series Seed Preferred.<br>Note: the value allocated to the common stock in this example is not a final conclusion and would be adjusted to incorporate applicable discounts.",
      "associatedImage": {
        "url": "carta/public/13/images/8696308067068407727_6rywbaOclam6OAfKD4W9CMz598fHa2uJIj0378OMKP5hRUebVtsoNqLAVaZxjfhNubqCMtgUOvynCCk0BLXTbK8q6uAsjUmyPsJnmbul9U5vXHJxcGA93RgcBb3LfxMFThMkv_fN"
